:::summary
The Old Testament — also called the Hebrew Bible — is the first and larger portion of Christian Scripture, comprising 39 books (Protestant) or 46 books (Catholic) that record God's creation of the world, his covenant with the people of Israel, his moral law given through Moses, and his prophetic promises pointing forward to the Messiah. Far from being superseded by the New Testament, the Old Testament is the essential foundation without which the life, death, and resurrection of Jesus Christ cannot be understood.
:::

